steps {
  type: CORTEX_STEP_TYPE_USER_INPUT
  status: CORTEX_STEP_STATUS_DONE
  metadata {
    created_at {
      seconds: 1779404578
      nanos: 161432053
    }
    source: CORTEX_STEP_SOURCE_USER_EXPLICIT
  }
  user_input {
    user_response: "# Technical Specification: Massively Instanced Particle Crowd (Lusion Aesthetic)\n\n## 1. Executive Summary\n\n**Objective:** Build a real-time WebGL application rendering a crowd of people formed entirely of luminous, amber/gold particles in a dark void.\n**Core Challenge:** Replicating the provided reference image requires hundreds of thousands, potentially over a million, individual particles. The application must maintain 60fps on mid-tier discrete GPUs and Apple Silicon.\n**Strict Constraint:** Standard mesh instantiation (even InstancedMesh) controlled by the CPU will fail. All particle transformation, physics, and state management **must** occur on the GPU using GPGPU techniques and custom shaders.\n\n## 2. Technology Stack\n\n| Layer | Technology / Package | Justification |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| **Core Rendering** | three (latest) | WebGL rendering engine. |\n| **Framework** | @react-three/fiber | Declarative scene graph and lifecycle management. |\n| **Utilities** | @react-three/drei | Pre-built helpers (camera controls, FBO hooks). |\n| **Post-Processing** | @react-three/postprocessing | Essential for the luminous bloom effect. |\n| **GPGPU** | Custom GLSL / FBO | Frame Buffer Objects for GPU-side position/velocity computation. |\n\n## 3. Asset Preparation Pipeline (Pre-computation)\n\nDo not load full 3D human models into the client at runtime. We only need their surface data.\n\n1. **Source Assets:** Procure 10\342\200\22315 low-poly, rigged human animations (idle standing, slight shifting).\n2. **Surface Sampling:** Create a Node.js build script using Three.js MeshSurfaceSampler.\n3. **Data Packing:** For each frame of the idle animations, sample 10,000 to 50,000 points on the surface of the meshes.\n4. **Output Format:** Pack these XYZ coordinates into a raw binary format (Float32Array) or pre-encode them into RGB data textures (.exr or .png if precision allows). The client will load these textures, not .gltf geometry.\n\n## 4. Architecture: The GPGPU FBO System\n\nTo achieve the fluid, slightly chaotic nature of the particles, we will use an FBO (Frame Buffer Object) ping-pong technique.\n\n### The Simulation Shader (Data Updating)\n\n* **Purpose:** Calculate the physics, wandering, and snapping of particles to their target human silhouettes without CPU intervention.\n* **Inputs:**\n* uCurrentPosition: Texture containing the current XYZ of all particles.\n* uTargetPosition: Texture containing the sampled surface points of the human meshes.\n* uTime: For driving Simplex noise.\n\n\n* **Logic:** Particles should smoothly interpolate (mix) toward their assigned uTargetPosition. Add 3D Simplex curl noise to their velocity to create the loose, \"alive\" feeling from the reference image.\n\n### The Render Shader (Visual Output)\n\n* **Purpose:** Draw the actual particles to the screen using the data calculated by the Simulation Shader.\n* **Geometry:** A single THREE.BufferGeometry containing only vertices (no faces). Rendered via .\n* **Vertex Shader:**\n* Read the particle\'s XYZ position from the FBO texture.\n* Set gl_Position.\n* Calculate gl_PointSize based on camera distance (particles closer to the camera must be larger) and a random size attribute injected at initialization.\n\n\n* **Fragment Shader (The Aesthetic):**\n* **NO HARD EDGES:** Do not load a texture file for the particle. Compute a radial gradient mathematically using gl_PointCoord. Distance from the center of the point coordinate should dictate alpha.\n* **Coloring:** Mix between warm amber (#FF8C00) and bright gold (#FFD700).\n* **Blending:** blending={THREE.AdditiveBlending} and depthWrite={false} are strictly required. This allows overlapping particles to accumulate light, naturally creating the brighter, concentrated clusters seen in the reference.\n\n\n\n## 5. Implementation of the \"Standout Figure\"\n\nThe reference image features one central cluster that is brighter, more concentrated, and highly active.\n\n* **Approach:** Reserve a specific section of your DataTexture (e.g., the first 50,000 pixels) exclusively for this figure.\n* **Shader Flags:** Pass a uniform or attribute into the Render Shader that flags these specific particles.\n* **Visual Distinction:** Multiply their base brightness by a factor of 2.0. Increase the frequency of their curl noise in the Simulation Shader to make them appear more \"energetic\" and less bound to a strict silhouette than the background crowd.\n\n## 6. Post-Processing (Crucial for the \"Lusion\" Look)\n\nThe raw WebGL output will look flat. The \"light in a dark space\" aesthetic relies entirely on high-quality Bloom.\n\n* Implement the Bloom effect from @react-three/postprocessing.\n* **Settings:**\n* mipmapBlur={true}: Essential for creating the soft, wide-spreading light bleed rather than a cheap, tight glow.\n* luminanceThreshold={0.5}: Ensure the dark background remains pitch black and only the denser particle clusters trigger the bloom.\n* intensity={1.5}: Adjust based on the additive blending accumulation.\n\n\n\n## 7. Performance Budget & Metrics\n\n* **Draw Calls:** Must remain under **20**. The entire crowd should ideally be a single draw call, with a few extra for post-processing and FBO ping-ponging.\n* **CPU Usage:** The JavaScript main thread should be virtually empty during the render loop. useFrame should only update uTime uniforms.\n* **Memory:** Ensure FBO textures are sized power-of-two (e.g., 1024x1024 = 1,048,576 particles). Use THREE.HalfFloatType for FBO data textures if supported by the client device to halve GPU memory bandwidth compared to FloatType."
    items {
      text: "# Technical Specification: Massively Instanced Particle Crowd (Lusion Aesthetic)\n\n## 1. Executive Summary\n\n**Objective:** Build a real-time WebGL application rendering a crowd of people formed entirely of luminous, amber/gold particles in a dark void.\n**Core Challenge:** Replicating the provided reference image requires hundreds of thousands, potentially over a million, individual particles. The application must maintain 60fps on mid-tier discrete GPUs and Apple Silicon.\n**Strict Constraint:** Standard mesh instantiation (even InstancedMesh) controlled by the CPU will fail. All particle transformation, physics, and state management **must** occur on the GPU using GPGPU techniques and custom shaders.\n\n## 2. Technology Stack\n\n| Layer | Technology / Package | Justification |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| **Core Rendering** | three (latest) | WebGL rendering engine. |\n| **Framework** | @react-three/fiber | Declarative scene graph and lifecycle management. |\n| **Utilities** | @react-three/drei | Pre-built helpers (camera controls, FBO hooks). |\n| **Post-Processing** | @react-three/postprocessing | Essential for the luminous bloom effect. |\n| **GPGPU** | Custom GLSL / FBO | Frame Buffer Objects for GPU-side position/velocity computation. |\n\n## 3. Asset Preparation Pipeline (Pre-computation)\n\nDo not load full 3D human models into the client at runtime. We only need their surface data.\n\n1. **Source Assets:** Procure 10\342\200\22315 low-poly, rigged human animations (idle standing, slight shifting).\n2. **Surface Sampling:** Create a Node.js build script using Three.js MeshSurfaceSampler.\n3. **Data Packing:** For each frame of the idle animations, sample 10,000 to 50,000 points on the surface of the meshes.\n4. **Output Format:** Pack these XYZ coordinates into a raw binary format (Float32Array) or pre-encode them into RGB data textures (.exr or .png if precision allows). The client will load these textures, not .gltf geometry.\n\n## 4. Architecture: The GPGPU FBO System\n\nTo achieve the fluid, slightly chaotic nature of the particles, we will use an FBO (Frame Buffer Object) ping-pong technique.\n\n### The Simulation Shader (Data Updating)\n\n* **Purpose:** Calculate the physics, wandering, and snapping of particles to their target human silhouettes without CPU intervention.\n* **Inputs:**\n* uCurrentPosition: Texture containing the current XYZ of all particles.\n* uTargetPosition: Texture containing the sampled surface points of the human meshes.\n* uTime: For driving Simplex noise.\n\n\n* **Logic:** Particles should smoothly interpolate (mix) toward their assigned uTargetPosition. Add 3D Simplex curl noise to their velocity to create the loose, \"alive\" feeling from the reference image.\n\n### The Render Shader (Visual Output)\n\n* **Purpose:** Draw the actual particles to the screen using the data calculated by the Simulation Shader.\n* **Geometry:** A single THREE.BufferGeometry containing only vertices (no faces). Rendered via .\n* **Vertex Shader:**\n* Read the particle\'s XYZ position from the FBO texture.\n* Set gl_Position.\n* Calculate gl_PointSize based on camera distance (particles closer to the camera must be larger) and a random size attribute injected at initialization.\n\n\n* **Fragment Shader (The Aesthetic):**\n* **NO HARD EDGES:** Do not load a texture file for the particle. Compute a radial gradient mathematically using gl_PointCoord. Distance from the center of the point coordinate should dictate alpha.\n* **Coloring:** Mix between warm amber (#FF8C00) and bright gold (#FFD700).\n* **Blending:** blending={THREE.AdditiveBlending} and depthWrite={false} are strictly required. This allows overlapping particles to accumulate light, naturally creating the brighter, concentrated clusters seen in the reference.\n\n\n\n## 5. Implementation of the \"Standout Figure\"\n\nThe reference image features one central cluster that is brighter, more concentrated, and highly active.\n\n* **Approach:** Reserve a specific section of your DataTexture (e.g., the first 50,000 pixels) exclusively for this figure.\n* **Shader Flags:** Pass a uniform or attribute into the Render Shader that flags these specific particles.\n* **Visual Distinction:** Multiply their base brightness by a factor of 2.0. Increase the frequency of their curl noise in the Simulation Shader to make them appear more \"energetic\" and less bound to a strict silhouette than the background crowd.\n\n## 6. Post-Processing (Crucial for the \"Lusion\" Look)\n\nThe raw WebGL output will look flat. The \"light in a dark space\" aesthetic relies entirely on high-quality Bloom.\n\n* Implement the Bloom effect from @react-three/postprocessing.\n* **Settings:**\n* mipmapBlur={true}: Essential for creating the soft, wide-spreading light bleed rather than a cheap, tight glow.\n* luminanceThreshold={0.5}: Ensure the dark background remains pitch black and only the denser particle clusters trigger the bloom.\n* intensity={1.5}: Adjust based on the additive blending accumulation.\n\n\n\n## 7. Performance Budget & Metrics\n\n* **Draw Calls:** Must remain under **20**. The entire crowd should ideally be a single draw call, with a few extra for post-processing and FBO ping-ponging.\n* **CPU Usage:** The JavaScript main thread should be virtually empty during the render loop. useFrame should only update uTime uniforms.\n* **Memory:** Ensure FBO textures are sized power-of-two (e.g., 1024x1024 = 1,048,576 particles). Use THREE.HalfFloatType for FBO data textures if supported by the client device to halve GPU memory bandwidth compared to FloatType."
    }
  }
}
