  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Considering Next Steps**\n\nOkay, I\'ve got the initial packages set up, and I\'m now focusing on the user\'s request. My current aim is to tackle a real-time WebGL application. The plan is to create a crowd made of luminous particles. The look should have a Lusion aesthetic, using amber/gold colors.\n\n\n**Analyzing Asset Preparation**\n\nOkay, I\'m now digging into asset preparation. The spec is clear: no full 3D models at runtime. My focus shifts to surface data. I\'m leaning toward a Node.js script using Three.js\'s MeshSurfaceSampler. Alternatively, could I generate human figures procedurally or load geometries directly? The plan involves packing XYZ coordinates into a raw binary format, potentially using RGB data textures. This will be the client\'s source.\n\n\n**Exploring Procedural Generation**\n\nI\'m now thinking about how to build those elegant human shapes. The plan is to explore procedural generation using cylinders, spheres, lofts, and lines as meshes to generate a variety of poses that I can sample with `MeshSurfaceSampler`. My goal is to avoid heavy external assets by pre-calculating them or generating them at client startup. I can pack XYZ coordinates into raw binary or pre-encode them into RGB data textures.\n\n\n**Defining Procedural Geometry**\n\nI\'m now zeroing in on defining human form mathematically. I\'m breaking down the body into fundamental shapes: spheres for heads, cylinders/capsules for torsos and limbs, and boxes/capsules for hands and feet. The goal is to generate 10-15 figures with pose variations via a procedural sampler, ensuring a zero-asset approach. I\'m leaning toward point coordinate generation. I\'m exploring representing animations mathematically via bones or a series of skinned shapes.\n\n\n**Implementing Vertex Animation**\n\nI\'m now writing a generator function for 3D humans with specific body part primitives like capsules and spheres. I\'m focusing on defining a skeleton with torso, head, neck, arms, and legs. My key thought is: if I generate multiple frames, I can save them in a texture or pack them into Float32Arrays! The texture size needs to be power-of-two.\n\n\n**Evaluating FBO Integration**\n\nI\'m now determining how to integrate FBO (Frame Buffer Object) for particle simulation within Three.js. After calculating the total particle count (300,000-360,000), a single 1024x1024 texture seems appropriate. The workflow involves a simulation shader to read current positions and compute the next based on various forces. Since Drei doesn\'t offer a generic GPGPU helper, I\'ll build a custom FBO system with a ping-pong state for positions, which will run within React.\n\n\n**Implementing Render Targets**\n\nOkay, I\'m now structuring the FBO implementation details. The plan involves a ping-pong rendering approach. I\'ll pass the current position render target as a texture uniform and read it within the vertex shader. The key thought is how to define the target positions for these figures to form a crowd. My initial layout involves 14 figures positioned across a floor to form the crowd, with specific world coordinates for each. The standout figure is at (0, 0, 0), and I\'ve planned out coordinates for the other 13 figures as well, with each figure containing 32,768 particles, which means around 460K vertices!\n\n\n**Calculating Particle Capacity**\n\nI\'ve just confirmed the particle density: around 450K total! I\'m now verifying if a 512x1024 FBO texture, with its 524,288 pixels, can accommodate this count. Thankfully, it fits perfectly! My key idea is using FBO texture columns to correspond to particles. I\'ll compute 2D texture coordinates in the vertex shader using the `reference` attribute.\n\n\n**Designing Target Positions**\n\nI\'m now focusing on defining the target positions for particles. I\'ve realized I can procedurally generate a target position texture at startup in JavaScript. This will feed into our simulation shader as a static texture, giving us high-precision 3D human meshes with no big downloads! I\'m planning to create 3D human geometries by creating a head, torso, etc.\n\n\n**Constructing Figure Geometries**\n\nOkay, I\'m now crafting individual human figures. I\'m focusing on defining body parts: a cylinder torso at (0, 1.0, 0), a sphere head at (0, 1.5, 0), and cylinder arms and legs. I\'m aiming to build a function `createHumanGeometry` to handle various poses and scales. The goal is 8 distinct figures/animation frames. I\'m planning to use `MeshSurfaceSampler` to extract point data from each generated figure.\n\n\n**Verifying Sampler Integration**\n\nI\'m now integrating the `MeshSurfaceSampler` and testing with `THREE.Mesh`es. I\'ve confirmed I can merge human figure sub-meshes into a single geometry. Now, I\'m defining a `sampleHumanPoints` function, it\'s amazingly simple and elegant. I\'m building it to sample a specific number of points from the mesh!\n\n\n**Merging Geometries Effectively**\n\nI\'m now integrating `BufferGeometryUtils` to merge body parts efficiently. It\'s awesome and incredibly powerful! I can build a `MeshSurfaceSampler` for the merged mesh. I\'m focusing on designing 8 distinct human poses: normal idle, hand-on-hip, cross-armed, thoughtful, elegant shift, conversing, wonder, and walking/stride poses. I can procedurally create these 8 geometries and construct distinct human poses.\n\n\n**Defining Crowd Instances**\n\nI\'m now calculating the final crowd composition, leveraging previously designed poses and figure offsets. The plan is to have 14 distinct figures, each exhibiting a unique pose and position. I\'ve designed the positions for each, including the standout figure at (0, 0, 0). The workflow involves each of the 14 figures being populated with particles, with poses assigned to each figure. I\'m now exploring the prospect of animating these figures. I\'m going to look for low-poly rigged human animations to add some life, even the slightest shifting will be great.\n\n\n**Animating Crowd Points**\n\nI\'m now thinking about animations. The focus is to make the crowd dynamically interactive in the simulation shader! I can make particles breathe and sway using curl noise or sine waves. We can also blend between poses, or make the points of each person move slightly with a combination of breathing, idle swaying, and snapping/morphing. We can allow the user to change the crowd state. This will be an interactive feature that fits the Lusion aesthetic! We can start by sampling 10,000 to 50,000 points on the surface of the meshes, which the client will then load as textures.\n\n\n**Exploring Simulation Modes**\n\nI\'m now outlining different simulation modes for interactive user control, keeping the Lusion aesthetic in mind. I\'m focusing on \"Crowd Silhouette,\" \"Dynamic Wandering,\" \"Ascension/Swirl Vortex,\" and \"Constellation/Galaxy\" modes, with thoughts on how the simulation shader should be designed. The modes will allow particles to interpolate towards their uTargetPosition, while using uTime for noise in the shader, per the technical requirements. Each mode will use a smooth interpolation (mix) operation! I\'ll ensure all transformation and physics are on the GPU.\n\n\n\n**Defining Simulation Logic**\n\nI\'m now focusing on writing out the logic for the simulation shader. I\'m prioritizing understanding how the FBO Ping-Pong system works within Three.js. Key to this is calculating particle velocities, incorporating curl noise for that lively feel. I\'m focusing on the \"standout figure\" and how to manage the separate section in the texture. Finally, I\'m thinking about setting gl_PointSize based on camera distance.\n\n\n\n"
    thinking_duration {
      seconds: 22
      nanos: 150229893
    }
    stop_reason: STOP_REASON_STOP_PATTERN
  }
}
