  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Confirming Project Structure**\n\nI\'ve confirmed the `package.json` setup is standard for a React Vite SPA. The \"dev\" script, configured as `vite --port=3000 --host=0.0.0.0`, is directly using the specified port. This indicates no need for full-stack Express server configuration; the current structure seems sufficient.\n\n\n**Validating Application Design**\n\nI\'ve validated that a client-side-only React SPA is the correct approach, given the user\'s requirements for a real-time WebGL canvas application. It seems a full-stack backend and a Gemini key are unnecessary. Now I\'m focusing on the procedural generation and FBO system design. I\'ve started outlining a modular structure, including `src/types.ts`, `src/utils/proceduralHuman.ts`, shader files (`simulationShader.ts`, `renderShader.ts`), and a `GPGPUParticles.tsx` component. This will keep `App.tsx` cleaner.\n\n\n**Designing Procedural Geometry**\n\nI\'m now focusing on designing the math for procedural human figures. My goal is to use parameterized equations to generate the skeletons directly in `src/utils/proceduralHuman.ts`. This approach promises better performance, zero startup delay, no external file dependencies, and customizable silhouettes, making for a robust implementation. I\'m breaking down the human shape into parts \342\200\223 starting with the torso, specifically a vertical capsule/cylinder.\n\n\n**Constructing Capsule-Based Sampling**\n\nI\'m now focusing on sampling points directly on the surface of capsule-shaped bones. The initial approach involves selecting a parametric value to get a point on the line segment connecting the capsule endpoints. I\'ll need to use this with the endpoints and radius. My focus is now on efficiently generating these capsule shapes, and eventually, the full procedural geometry.\n\n\n**Defining Bone-Based Volumes**\n\nI\'m now refining the cylinder generation to create volume. Adding `V * r` to `P` directly samples points on the cylinder\'s surface. To add variance, I can jitter the point or sample within its volume. This provides a luminous and ethereal look. I\'ve formulated a `Pose Skeleton` structure using interfaces for `Joint` and `Bone`, planning to define various poses with different bone configurations. The `Bone` interface includes `id`, `start`, `end`, `radius`, and `weight` properties. I\'m starting with an \"Idle Standing\" pose.\n\n\n**Defining Pose Parameters**\n\nI\'m now detailing an \"Idle Standing\" pose and a \"Waving\" pose within the `Pose Skeleton` structure. I\'ve defined bone positions, radii, and start/end points using capsule-based geometry, with spheres for the heads. Currently, I\'m using these parameters to create the procedural human skeleton. This should provide a basis for animation.\n\n\n**Defining Additional Poses**\n\nI\'m now detailing poses beyond the base \"Idle Standing\" state. I\'m expanding my \"Pose Skeleton\" data structure. Specifically, I\'m working on defining the bone configurations and radii for new poses: \"Thinking/Hand on Chin\", \"Arms Folded\", and \"Dynamic Shift (Swaying/Dancing).\" My focus is on generating a variety of dynamic character poses.\n\n\n**Defining Additional Poses**\n\nI\'m now detailing poses beyond the base \"Idle Standing\" state. I\'m expanding my \"Pose Skeleton\" data structure. Specifically, I\'m working on defining the bone configurations and radii for new poses: \"Hero Stand (Hands on Hips)\" \"Graceful Look Up / Reaching\", and \"Slight Shifting Walk\". My focus is on generating a variety of dynamic character poses.\n\n\n**Calculating Sampling Weights**\n\nI\'m now calculating bone-specific sampling weights. I\'m assigning Torso the highest weight (0.30) for core body density, followed by Head (0.18) for clarity. I\'m distributing the remaining weight across the other bones. I\'m focusing on defining each bone\'s contribution to the overall procedural human structure. My focus is on achieving a balanced and detailed distribution of points across the figure.\n\n\n\n**Refining Sampling Logic**\n\nI\'m now refining the sampling logic, ensuring a uniform distribution. I have verified that I\'ve achieved a perfect weight distribution among the bones, making sure each bone\'s contribution is precisely defined. I\'m focusing on the implementation details for drawing samples from a selected bone, including handling the case where start equals end. The next steps will involve calculating perpendicular directions, ensuring random point generation on the bone surface. I\'ll need to define the code to create random vectors for head or endcap radius generation.\n\n\n**Implementing Cylinder Sampling**\n\nI\'m now implementing the cylinder sampling logic in detail, having confirmed its mathematical correctness. I\'m excited about the approach, as the cylinder generator will create a list of points per figure, with a range of 10,000 to 50,000 points. I\'m focusing on handling `theta`, random radius factor `u`, and the offset from the bone spine. I\'m planning to introduce parameters like base poses, position offset, scaling, and rotation. These will allow for a diverse crowd of 14 figures.\n\n\n**Integrating GPGPU Technique**\n\nI\'m now integrating the GPGPU technique into the design. I\'ve focused on how to represent particle data using textures, specifically storing positions in an appropriately sized texture. The red, green, and blue channels will contain the X, Y, Z coordinates, and the alpha channel will be used to store a flag to identify the \"standout figure\". I\'m planning this for future shader work to calculate and update particle positions. I\'m focusing on the implementation details now.\n\n\n**Implementing Ping-Pong Buffering**\n\nI\'m implementing the ping-pong buffering scheme using two `WebGLRenderTargets`, `rtA` and `rtB`, of size `W x H`. At each frame, I\'ll set `uCurrentPosition` to `rtA.texture`, render the simulation shader onto `rtB`, swap them, and then use `rtA.texture` for the final point rendering. The initial positions for `rtA` and `rtB` will be from a `THREE.DataTexture` initialized with target values or a scattered cloud. This initialization will occur on the first frame.\n\n\n**Verifying Data Texture Format**\n\nI\'m now investigating potential device support issues with the data texture format. While modern WebGL2 is preferred, I need to ensure broad compatibility. After a quick review, I\'ll use `THREE.FloatType` for maximal precision, with a fallback to `THREE.HalfFloatType` if needed, as modern Three.js handles this elegantly. I have also double-checked the simulation shader.\n\n\n\n**Implementing Noise in GLSL**\n\nI\'m now implementing 3D Simplex noise directly within the simulation shader. I\'ve chosen a standard Ashima Arts implementation for its robustness and efficiency. I\'m focusing on integrating this into the shader to add high-quality noise.\n\n\n**Integrating Noise**\n\nI\'m now integrating 3D Simplex noise to the simulation, using an Ashima Arts implementation. The focus is on seamlessly adding this noise directly within the simulation shader, which will enhance the quality of the procedural generation.\n\n\n**Calculating Curl Noise**\n\nI\'m now focusing on calculating curl noise from the existing 3D Simplex noise implementation. I\'m aiming to compute the curl field for vector field simulations using the gradient of the noise function. I\'m exploring methods to efficiently approximate the spatial derivatives in the GLSL shader.\n\n\n**Implementing Curl Noise**\n\nI\'ve successfully integrated a method for calculating curl noise based on 3D Simplex noise within the shader. The approximation produces spectacular results, allowing the particles to swirl and drift with organic fluid-like motion. I\'m now testing and tuning its parameters.\n\n\n\n**Refining Simulation Logic**\n\nI\'m now refining the simulation logic within the GLSL shader, focusing on transitioning between crowd and vortex modes based on `uChaos`. In vortex mode, particles now follow a cylindrical upward spiral, dynamically shaped by sine functions and random offsets.  I\'m also considering adding damping to the positions to prevent infinite acceleration. I\'ve now introduced `uDamping` for this control.\n\n\n**Adjusting Particle Physics**\n\nI\'m now refining the particle physics with a more detailed GLSL implementation, now including crowd and vortex modes. I\'m dynamically shaping a cylindrical upward spiral in vortex mode with sine functions. I\'ve also incorporated damping to manage acceleration, controlled by `uDamping`. The `finalTarget` integrates crowd behavior with the vortex, and I\'m using `uChaos` for the blend. I\'m now also including a \"return force\" for the standout figure.\n\n\n**Enhancing Physics Simulations**\n\nI\'m now focusing on refining the physics simulations to enrich the visual effects, particularly with enhanced noise and mouse interaction. I\'ve integrated standout figure-specific noise with higher frequency and strength to generate more unique and vibrant behavior. I\'m introducing a mouse interaction force. I\'ve also incorporated velocity clamping to manage particle speeds. The next stage is to store the updated positions.\n\n\n\n"
    thinking_duration {
      seconds: 36
      nanos: 985558942
    }
