    thinking: "**Designing Crowd Particles**\n\nI\'m currently focused on designing the `generateCrowdParticles` function within `src/utils/proceduralHuman.ts`. The initial plan involves creating a 2D grid, returning `{ positions: Float32Array; standouts: Float32Array }` as the structure for the crowd particles data. I\'ll need to figure out how to efficiently organize particle data with the given dimensions.\n\n\n**Calculating Particle Allocations**\n\nI\'ve been calculating how to allocate crowd particles within the texture. Considering a 512x1024 texture (524,288 pixels), I\'m exploring an uneven distribution across 14 figures. I\'ve decided on the following: standout figure with 65,536 particles (first 128 rows), and then several other figures. I will now allocate particles to figures 7 - 13.\n\n\n**Allocating Particle Figures**\n\nI\'ve finalized the allocation of particle figures within the texture, ensuring an exact fit. I\'ve confirmed 15 distinct figures can fit perfectly into the 512x1024 texture. Figure 0 (standout) uses 128 rows, and figures 1-14 each use 64 rows. This results in 524,288 particles total, which is exactly the texture\'s capacity. I\'m excited about the density of the standout figure! Now I am thinking about how to position these in the crowd.\n\n\n**Defining Figure Positions**\n\nI\'ve been defining the 3D positions, rotations, and scales for each figure within the crowd. The standout figure will be at the origin, majestic and scaled up. Each subsequent figure will have a unique position, rotation, and scale, creating a visually interesting and dynamic crowd composition. It\'s an incredibly exciting approach.\n\n\n**Creating Crowd Textures**\n\nI\'m now writing the `generateCrowdTextures` function within `src/utils/proceduralHuman.ts`. I\'m focusing on defining 8 base poses to cycle through for the 15 figures. Each pixel in the `Float32Array` will store RGBA values (XYZ coordinates and an identifier/offset). The generator will consist of poses, sample points, and the main function returning particle positions.\n\n\n"
