  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Developing GPGPU Particles**\n\nI\'ve finished the simulation and render shaders! Now, I\'m focusing on crafting the GPGPU Particles system within `src/components/GPGPUParticles.tsx`. But before I dive in, I need to figure out the best way to integrate GPGPU and FBO within React Three Fiber \342\200\223 specifically, I\'m envisioning a dedicated component.\n\n\n**Defining Data Textures**\n\nI\'m now zeroing in on defining the data textures necessary for the GPGPU simulation. I\'ve determined the need for two `THREE.WebGLRenderTarget`s, employing a ping-pong technique. I\'m opting for `FloatType` to store the coordinates within the textures, with specific settings to ensure no filtering or clamping. Using `useMemo` and `useFrame`, I\'ll create `targetTexture` and `initialTexture` from the `generateCrowdTextures` function.\n\n\n**Implementing Simulation Logic**\n\nOkay, I\'m now setting up the core simulation rendering logic. I\'ve established an initial configuration with `rt0` and `rt1` FBO render targets (512x1024). I\'ve created a dedicated simulation scene with an orthographic camera and a plane mesh, employing a custom simulation material. In `useFrame`, I\'m fetching the WebGL renderer and computing delta time. Then, I\'m updating the material uniforms, including current and target positions, initial positions, time, delta time, and various chaos parameters. Finally, I\'ll set the active render target to `rt1` and render the simulation scene.\n\n\n**Refining Interaction Integration**\n\nI\'m now integrating cursor interaction into the simulation! I am implementing smooth cursor projections onto a plane for dynamic particle responses. Within `useFrame`, I\'m figuring out how to get mouse coordinates. This involves projecting 2D mouse coordinates into 3D space, which will require raycasting and vector transformations within the React Three Fiber environment. I\'m focusing on defining projected coordinates to dynamically trigger particle reactions based on the user\'s cursor.\n\n\n**Optimizing Mouse Projections**\n\nI\'ve refined the cursor projection, focusing on accuracy across the scene\'s depth. I am now projecting the mouse onto a z-plane at z=-1.5, or, if the projection is unsafe, onto a default distance. I also ensure robust initialization of GPGPU texture targets. Specifically, I\'m verifying the initial positions from `initialTexture` are copied into the render targets `rt0` and `rt1` upon component mount, ensuring proper particle starting locations. I am crafting a system to accomplish this.\n\n\n**Initializing Render Targets**\n\nI\'ve crafted a method to address the initialization of my GPGPU texture targets. I\'m taking the `initialTexture` and using it to populate `rt0` and `rt1` render targets on the first frame. This involves a custom shader and a simple quad rendered onto both buffers. The provided snippet demonstrates this perfectly! I am now ensuring this step is executed only once and is properly integrated into my `useFrame` loop.\n\n\n**Constructing Vertex Buffers**\n\nI\'m now implementing the particle vertex buffer geometry. I\'m focusing on defining three key attributes: dummy positions (initialized to zero), texture references representing UV coordinates, and random sizes for size variation. Specifically, I\'m constructing dummyPositions, which are initialized to zeros since the vertex shader will override the positions. I\'m also preparing references, calculating the UV coordinates for each particle, and aRandomSize with random floats between 0.5 and 1.5 for each particle.\n\n\n**Defining Prop Definitions**\n\nI\'m now determining the prop definitions for the `GPGPUParticles` component. I\'ve compiled a list of parameters for user control, including \'chaos,\' \'noiseStrength,\' and color options. My plan is to assemble this file and use `useRef` to handle the Three.js objects through React Three Fiber hooks. I am now figuring out exactly how to set up the necessary react refs.\n\n\n"
    thinking_duration {
      seconds: 21
      nanos: 986255905
    }
    stop_reason: STOP_REASON_STOP_PATTERN
  }
}
